Yes, there is a potential issue here with the incentive building for new keys, and I believe it is due to a combination of factors that we'll address hopefully in the next week. In particular, it is the combination of the validator exponential moving average window being too wide, and due to the validator excluding the lowest 10% percentile from weight setting.

We know how to address these issues, but they are in place for a reason, primarily to incentivize competition by forcing new keys to reasonably exceed the average performance. However, it seems the network may have reached a point where this stimulated competition is too aggressive, in which case the remedy is to reduce the validator EMA window so it saturates new scores faster (we have a live PR already), and potentially the exclusion quantile being dropped.

The team will discuss and analyze the root cause for this issue this week, and come back with a solution. Thanks for raising the issue and providing the details and proofs.

Disclaimer: above is just my opinion, and have to consult with the team before a more official response can be made.

👏👏👏 thanks for the communication and update . Im curious as to what the team thinks or what their opinion is on this mass key regger. Do you think this could have a negative effect on the network?

I was telling my dad over dinner last night how complicated it must be to distribute incentive equitably on an ongoing basis, how in this kind of a network everything is constantly shifting and the team has to deal with ever-changing circumstances adjusting a live network... that it must be complex and a many a headache at times.... and of course i don't even know the half of it.

Yw. Potentially it can have a negative effect, although we rely on the built-in mechanisms to protect the important aspects. In particular, regging lots of keys is wasted effort if they can't stay regged, so they'll have to serve very good models to push out incumbent miners, and better models are good for the network. On the other hand, regging dominance can prevent others from playing, especially if they may have good model building skills that could be advantageous to the network. One solution has been talked about before, potentially replacing PoW with model evaluation, so candidate miners are actually tested on what's important to the network. I still see this as a possibility, but not prioritized right now.

Hello all, I am new here.
What's the difference between "competitive Server" and "validator"? 
To earn TAO, which kind of server should I be running?

If you are new here I suggest you to spend 2 days here on Discord and use the search function for every issue/question that you have. Regarding your question, "competitive server" can be simply called "a miner/a server". Mining TAO isn't like mining ETH/BTC. You will be in a "competition" with other active miners in the Bittensor network and you should come up with a good fine tune model in order to be able to remain in the network and not be deregistered.

Hi @Eseck  I appreciate your advice, I have been searching in different channels and trying to understand from bits and pieces 🙂
  Also thank you so much for the details about Competitive Server. 
One more follow up question: If I decide to go with "Validator" server, do I not need to compete to remain registered, but will get less rewards?
If you have at least 1024 TAO in your hotkey you can run a validator node.
And no, you won't have that deregistration problem anymore.

For anyone unable to withdraw funds from ftx

Shorting SOL: A risky but alpha way to do synthetic withdrawals from FTX.  Long an asset on FTX and short the same one on Binance.  In the case of the world where the acquisition deal goes through, you are roughly flat (lose a bit on the basis). In the case of the world where the acquisition falls through, the losses on FTX don't matter much because you can't get your money out anyway but you win on the short Binance leg.  This is of course assuming the market does collapse more in the case of no deal versus deal.
